## Phase 5 — Synthesise the report

Merge the SURVIVING findings into a markdown report. Use the `voice` above —
direct, specific names and numbers, no filler. Structure:

```
# MCP Analysis — last <N> days (<date>)

## TL;DR
3-5 bullets: the single biggest CHANGE this window (a spike / regression if
there is one — lead with it), the highest-confidence frustration, and the most
valuable fix.

## Major changes & trends
What MOVED over the window. Lead with any error-rate spike or NEW failure mode
(error code that first appeared mid-window = a regression — give the date, the
tool, the count). Then volume / active-user shifts, new users this week, and
version-adoption changes. Every claim cites its dates + numbers. Say "coincides
with", not "caused by", unless a trace proves the mechanism.

## Frustration themes
Per theme: what's happening · root cause (mechanism) · who hit it · evidence (verbatim).

## Root causes & fixes
Ranked by confidence. Split: [code-verifiable] vs [needs-investigation].
Each fix is a recommendation with its evidence — never a claim it's been done.

## Inferred feature requests
Only those that passed the ≥2-utterance rule. Each: the feature · the users ·
the verbatim prompts that imply it.

## Recommendations (prioritised — what to do next)
The action layer. Pull every SUPPORTED fix + feature request into ONE ranked
to-do list, ordered by impact × confidence (highest first). This is the part a
reader acts on, so keep it crisp — one line each:

`P1/P2/P3 · <action> · why (impact) · [code-verifiable | needs-investigation] · evidence ref`

Lead with anything that addresses a major-change regression (a fresh spike
usually outranks a steady background issue). Each recommendation must trace back
to a finding above — no new claims appear here (Iron Law #1). Still
recommendations, not actions (Iron Law #6): the skill proposes the to-do list,
it does not do it.

## Investigation prompts (for each `needs-investigation` item)
For EVERY fix/recommendation tagged `needs-investigation`, emit a ready-to-paste
prompt for a coding agent to FULLY investigate the root cause and propose a fix.
One fenced block per item, built from the template in Phase 5b. `code-verifiable`
items are skipped (they already have a concrete fix).

**If there are zero `needs-investigation` findings this window, do NOT bury it —
state it loudly as the section's only content:**

```
NOTHING TO IMPROVE THIS WINDOW — 0 actionable (needs-investigation) findings.
Reason: <pick the true one — e.g. "clean window, no failure themes survived
verification" / "all fixes are code-verifiable (already actionable, no
investigation needed)" / "data too thin to support a confident finding">.
```

This explicit "nothing to add" is a valid, expected outcome — a quiet window is
good news, not a skill failure. Never invent a finding to fill the section.

## Weak signals (single-utterance — not yet requests)
Things worth watching that didn't meet the bar.

## Blind spots & confidence (Iron Law #4)
Survivorship bias · prompt coverage __% · sample size · anything the data can't tell us.
```

Print the report. Also save it to `.context/mcp-analysis/<date>-<window>d.md` so
runs accumulate locally and can be diffed week-over-week.

**Phase 5 Gate — emit this block to close the run:**

